  <h2 id="spec">Write a specification</h2>

  <p>You should write a <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/buying-for-schools/writing-a-specification">specification</a> of what you need before you buy.</p>

  <p>A specification tells suppliers exactly what you need. Writing a specification may help you save time, money and ensure you get the right products for your pupils.

  <p>When writing a specification, you may want to consider if you need:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>teaching support, revision, assessment or intervention materials</li>
    <li>reading schemes, subscriptions, printed resources (fiction and non-fiction), digital (e-books) or a combination of both</li>
    <li>to target a specific group of pupils with 1 resource</li>
    <li>a complete, coherent programme or a resource that will support an existing programme</li>
  </ul>


  <h2 id="discounts">Discounts</h2>

  <p>To get discounts from suppliers, you can combine budgets across several departments, schools or an entire MAT. If you&rsquo;re not already linked with your local schools and would like to be, sign up to the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/join-or-create-a-network-for-school-business-professionals/school-business-professional-networks-directory">School Business Professional Networks</a>.</p>

  <p>For more support, get advice from colleagues, peers, subject associations and teaching hubs by following subject groups and influential teachers on Twitter, such as <a href="https://twitter.com/ukedchat">@ukedchat</a>.</p>



  <h2 id="find">Find the right way to buy</h2>

  <p>It&rsquo;s important to find the right way to buy depending on your circumstances. Here are three suggestions:</p>

  <h3>Use a framework</h3>

  <div class="cta-box">
    <p>The Department of Education (DfE) reviews a range of frameworks. These are assessed for compliance with procurement regulations, ease of use, suitability and value for money.</p>
    <p><a href="/service/">{{ locals.serviceName }}</a>.</p>
  </div>

  <p>Buying from a framework is usually quicker and easier than getting bids or quotes because the agreements:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>have already been through a full competitive tender process</li>
    <li>have been quality checked</li>
    <li>are checked to make sure they comply with the law</li>
    <li>may have draft specifications and help available</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The Department of Education (DfE) reviews a range of frameworks. These are assessed for compliance with procurement regulations, ease of use, suitability and value for money.</p>


  <h3>Use a catalogue or third party supplier</h3>

